translation:
Learn, from this point onward, the methods of yoga that annihilate madness,
[Those] mixed with hingu, sauvarcala, usira, and dvipala, blended with ghee in a pot;
Indeed, in the four-syllabled chant of the cow's mantra lies the success in suppressing madness.

Consisting of a mixture of Haritaki, Katphala, Udumbara, Pathedi, Arjuna, Dhanvana, and Kadamba, as well as both Haridra and Tagara, Viḍaṇga, and Śālā-Arjuna;

And also Khadira, Dhava, Surā, Va Kuṣṭha, Aguru, and Candana;

Two Phalā, three Sapāṭhā, Pathedi, Murvā, Śva-Daṃṣṭrā;

Yavani, Uśīra, Abhayā-Guḍūcī, Cavya, Ābhayā-Citraka, and seven Parṇāḥ;

Recommended for Kapha-Mehinām by ten upadiṣṭāḥ, these herbs, infused with madhu, are indeed a potent concoction, prepared with kaṣāyāḥ from various pādaiḥ.

[Verse 30:] Adorned with usheera, lodhras, kasturi, and candana, all of which instill fearlessness in the minds of those who apply it; sweetened with patala, nimba, and malaka fruits that taste like nectar, and further adorned with fearlessness-granting lotus, padma, and vriksha-kanya trees;

[Verse 31:] Adorned with lodhras grown in ambu, kali, yaka, dhataki plants, nimba and arjuna trees that are beneficial for health, and with shirisha, sarja, and arjuna kesara that resemble the color of gold, as well as adorned with priyangu, padma, utpala, and kimshuka flowers;

[Verse 32:] Adorned with asvattha, partha, and veta trees that are pure and sacred, having kaṭaṅka flowers at their tops, praised by the wise ones, and adorned with mustaka flowers; among these, ten types of mudras, prescribed for the feet, are to be performed correctly, which remove impurities and fill one's mind with sweetness.

His food is not cooked by the pains of the edema that has afflicted his body; his throat dries up, he experiences hunger, thirst, and the dimness of his ears;
The wasting away of his sides, back, neck, and head; excessive hiccups, distress, emaciation, and exhaustion;
The increase of all tastes and the establishment in the mind; the weakening and wasting away of his life force, health is attained when he eats;
He is a human being, subject to diseases like wind disorder, abdominal lump, and spleen disease, fearing consumption of old age, dryness, emaciation;
The repeated emergence of bile, phlegm, and wind, and the aggravation caused by Vayu.

From haritaki, take half the measure, and of āmalaka as well; add to it a tenth part of kapittha, then half of indravaruṇī;
In a quarter-droṇa, combine viḍaṅga, pippalī, lodhram, and marica, a gram each, along with twice that amount of śailavāluka.
To this, add half of the remaining juice of droṇa; then, in pure, cool water, soak guḍa for a hundred units of its own measure;
Of that, set aside a quarter for ghṛta-bhājana.

Combine in a pot the following: Gandiri, Ballataka, Citraka, Vyosa, Viddanga (in two Bṛhati measures),
Cook it thoroughly with ghee named Droṇa and cow dung, then offer Kurcika;
The remainder, divided into three portions, blend it with well-prepared Suputa-shita,
Along with one hundred Sitopala and apply it on the pot adorned with Citrakapippalina.
Established in the sky, propelled by Meru's force, it moves aloft;
Affected by bhagandara, arsha, krimi, kustha, meha, vaivarnya, kilasa, and anila, it is thus prepared.

The moon, promoting juiciness in ushira and lodhra, similarly in a city a Kirata does for bitter plants;
dhātakī and dhanvayā provide juice to bilva and others; a steady mudga exists;
in the west, date palms and barley, imagined to exist, yield cooling sap;
even in meats, juices exist; raktapittaghnya and sita herbs, used separately, alleviate thirst with their juices or provide coolness.
